caption:
There are many ways to understand a new land and its people; my favourite of all, is through its literature. As we travelled through Toyko, Hong Kong, Macau & Bangkok — each with massively different cultures and lifestyles, I studied the poetic forms and themes specific to each place, in a lead-up to this final documentation in poetry.

The poems in this series barely scratch the surface of rich cultures of different lands, and is but my naive attempt at taking it all in as best as I can, like a child curiously peeking over the fence en pointe, eyes eager and wide.
- @[1140788064:2048:Rachel Ang]

description:
Flying through dreams. The greatest in flight entertainment I've ever experienced. 

In the lead up to a trip home, I had been watching the aurora forecast, and knew that there was supposed to be a G1 magnetic storm the night of my flight. The day before leaving, I reserved a North facing window seat at the rear of the plane accordingly. I expected to see the lights later at night while flying over Manitoba/Ontario, but was happily surprised when they made a strong early appearance. The video begins over Southeastern Alberta just after 8PM local time, and ends near Thunder Bay. The brightest city is Winnipeg. 

To capture this timelapse, I extended a tripod and wedged it against the window seat, with the camera lens pressed against the glass. Airplane windows are very prone to reflections, so I blacked out the entire window with a sweater, leaving only the camera monitor showing through the back. Fortunately, I had an entire row to myself to play with cameras, and had another window to stare spellbound out of while reclining back. 

Sony a7s - f/4, 5", ISO 25600 - 1" interval between shots.
Music: Air - All I Need

message: We drive 30 minutes out of Doha city to a modern seaside strip that features every imaginable cuisine - Indian, Lebanese, Chinese, Japanese. It is called Souk Waqif, named after the old markets where people traded wares such as pearls and fish - items that made up the local economy before Qatar discovered its oil fields, and people still made their living off the sea. Waqif means standing, because the incoming tide kept traders on their feet as they bought and sold their goods. #visitqatar

Without any plans or research, other than my first host arranged, I scooted off to Istanbul right after a project ended. Spent 2 months backpacking solo all around Turkey staying entirely with strangers who eventually became friends, most of them I still keep in touch with! Hitchhiked A LOT, ATV, motorbike, hotairballoon, horse-riding, hiking, snorkeling, island-hopping, cave exploring, became a sunrise/sunset tour guide for new people that stayed at "my" hostel, build a proper campfire by a cave, got kissed (very passionately) by the 44degrees celsius sun, got proposed to, almost got married - everything were decisions I made with spontaneity. And, it was the best travel experience ever!! ;D one huge adventure, too many stories to tell!
I went to Montreal, ended up contracting H1N1 and spent 8 hours in a Montreal hospital, and the next few days in quarantine. Crazy!

I recently travelled to Japan for a family trip, and one of the last things on the itinerary was 3 days of skiing on the beautiful slopes of Hokkaido. After being continually mocked by friends back home, I decided to MAN UP and try snowboarding instead💪. Lessons seemed pretty lame and for little kids, so I decided to head straight for this massive, 100 meter slope with crazy drops, ridiculous inclines and a small forest in the middle to navigate around 😱😱. worst decision ever HAHA. ended up dislocating my shoulder traumatically on a huge wipeout, got stranded in the middle without any sight of help, slowly made my own way down and ran around the ski lodge with my arm completely out of the socket before finally finding my dad and getting to the hospital😂. craziest/most painful travel experience ever!!!

Last year, my friends and I backpacked an amazing route in China that touched some of the most culturally rich places of the country. But there was a price to pay (literally), because transport is expensive in such areas. So to save money, we decided to hitchhike. Of all our rides, the most memorable was the one from our last destination at Se Da. We managed to get a ride from a kind lady for 2 days and even stayed the night at her place when we arrived at the city! She treated us to all our meals (we tried to pay of course!), and introduced us to her entire family and all her friends we stop to eat with on the way. Hands down best hitchhiking experience ever! We still keep in touch till today! 

Come Vanesse Koh let's go cray.
I wish it was for people residing in other countries as well!

This was one of those moments that I really miss about my back packing trip last year. I was in Edinburgh at the time. My hostel friends rented a car to drive around Edinburgh and invited me along which was very kind of them. But I kinda felt that going on foot is the best way to get to know a foreign place. It is also usually the precursor to even more unexpected experiences or discoveries so naturally, I declined. I walked the entire day, first going North for awhile then changed to East then back to north again. It just felt like the right thing to do. Miraculously, I ended up at the base of Arthur's seat. "Shag" was the first word that came to mind when I saw how far I was from the top. But I climbed up anyway. Made friends with this group of US grad students who were trying to take that perfect synchronised jump shot. They really displayed true drive and grit in that 30 mins was what I told them. The view at the top was insane. You could see all of Edinburgh, beaches, all at one shot. I'm not doing any justice to the description but it was just so grand to see things from that perspective. You knew that everything was big and daunting if you think about their actual size but I remember thinking that they looked so small from this point that it seemed that you can take on the world you know. One of the guys found a slope that was pure soft grass with no rocks and so we spent the remainder of the day just laughing and laughing as we rolled in the grass. It was so nice to have that soothing breeze constantly caressing our faces too. I loved that day so much

We were wearing our yukatas and slippers and decided to make a dash for the convenience store in -2 degree weather. We thought the store was around the corner but ended up running through more than 5 blocks before finding our convenience store.

Being a Singaporean means our worst weather would be the scorching hot sun or at most, flooded roads. 
An impromptu trip with my travel buddy became a solo travel as she had to return home first, then I met with a typhoon and could not make it to Kaohsiung from Taipei where my hotel for the next 2 nights were booked. I then met up with a Taiwanese Friend who I knew from my previous trip (we started chatting and just hit it off really well and has been in contact since then, it has been 5 years!) 
Walking in the typhoon to her house, my luggage and me started flying off, I couldn't keep my feet planted and she was laughing while trying to stay standing too, but we decided to brave through it, get back to her house and went out again to get food and supplies, and she started calling her Friends and from a solo travel we became a party of 4 to drive down Kaohsiung the minute the typhoon cooled down! It was really impromptu and spontaneous but they were all so, so sweet and fun loving people I cannot wait to meet them again! 

As for my travel buddy, This time, I would really love to bring my hardworking, workaholic mum on a spontaneous trip, so maybe we'll go on a Mother-Daughter bonding trip! (Unable to tag as she does not use Facebook :)) 😬

Had this trip to Vietnam when the tour guide and the boat captain called me to share their bottle of local wine, i immediately agreed and drank the entire shot when they shook their heads cause of amazement. I wasnt aware it will fire back at me until it was my nth shot. I called all the other group companions of every nationality (australian, german, european and korean) to join and we had this wonderful conversations with wonderful strangers. I can't recall everything but i recalled knocking at a local's home if i can use their bathroom because my bladder was exploding. Good times, yes. It was March 2014

One of our most epic adventures happened while we were in Yellowknife, Canada. Joshua Ng's plane got delayed due to a snowstorm and I was worried sick for the whole night. That aside, we flew all the way there solely to view the northern lights, since they were predicted to dim for the next decade according to their 11-year solar cycle. Much to our dismay, the weather was terribly horrendous during our guided aurora hunting trip and all we did was to freeze outside the car while staring at the dark sky, imagining that any trace of city light was auroras. :'( Unfortunately, it was cloudy THROUGHOUT our entire 4 day stay there and the only light we saw was from the campfire beside the teepee (a traditional conical tent that in no way replaced the aurora hunting experience). The maple cookies served were delicious, but we paid quite a sum of money for the auroras so… Ouch.

While we were obviously disappointed, we still tried to salvage the situation as much as we could by being spontaneous. After all, the scenery was insanely beautiful even without the northern lights.

We decided to go hiking, dogsledding, and riding snow mobiles. Hiking in the snow suggested snowball fights, fist fights (with the snow as cushion), the frantic shaking of trees to bury one in snow, and more. Plus it’s free, and free things are often happy things. :D I was pretty certain that my face was frozen towards the end though. Through that, we bumped into a friendly local grandma (who was originally from Finland) and she brought us to her secret spot to view a frozen lake which was covered in snow. We also bumped into a couple who were walking their dogs. We found it adorable that their dogs were still running around searching for absent squirrels because they did not know that the squirrels were hibernating. A casual chat about the weather (-20 degrees Celsius) revealed that it was a tad “too warm”- a shocking perspective to hear considering that we were wearing 3 layers of thermal wear. Riding a snow mobile without a drivers’ license was awesome too. The wind was a tad too harsh for we drove too quickly (I mean, we were meant to speed on snow mobiles, right?) and my tears froze into ice after the trip, which kind of glued all my eyelashes together.

Being typical broke students, we tried to save money by sleeping in the airport overnight for one of our early flights. It turned out to be one of the most unwise and epic moves! Unfortunately, we wrongly assumed that the airport was 24/7 (!!!) and got chased out near midnight. Thankfully, the only restaurant open, McDonald’s, allowed us to crash for a while and even offered us free cookies. Afterwhich, we went to Shell to sit around as we waited for the airport to open. Dragging our luggage around in the snow in the middle of the night was definitely an ordeal. The saddest part was that our taxi fares, when combined, could have gotten us a decent room to stay. :(

That said, we enjoyed the experience thoroughly and still managed to catch the northern lights when we went to Banff.

:O this is so tough! There's always something epic in every adventure :x 

I'm just really glad to have a group of girlfriends that complement each other on every trip. We met on a work & travel program during university, that created lots of lasting, fond memories. We had a goal - to do our graduation trip/ European adventure together. We went in June 2013. It was the start our wanderlust (for pretty sceneries - castles, mountains, lakes, crazy adventures together) and a group of girls called #winebffs 🍷

It was epic because,
- 4 people boarded 3 different flights only to meet in Charles de Gaulle the next morning :) Different budgets, different times of ticket purchase. 
- We travelled together more than 80% and even split up in between because there was a slightly different plan on what we wanted to accomplish. haha. Has definitely shown me that everything is possible with trust and will! Just show up again at the agreed time and place!
- Met friends of friends in the different European cities! Fun! Let the locals, people whom are more familiar bring your on greater adventures! We visited many castles <3, museums, parks and more! We had awesome meals, tried local food, and most importantly- LOTS of alcohol. During that 3 weeks, I consumed the most alcohol ever. Everyday, almost every meal, because alcohol was cheaper than water. I found myself appreciating wine, white wine in particular. That was also how, we got ourselves the winebffs hashtag! (able to find us based on this hashtag on instagram! :D)

I'd say, the epitome was the day we had a full un-eaten roast chicken with us to "settle" as we were about to leave on the train for another city. We bought the chicken because it was 2 for something euros, and thought it'd settle us for a cheap and good meal. But, we didn't manage to settle the second one because we were running late on our schedule. When we reached the train station, we had time to spare, and that roast chicken. We all felt wasted if we just threw it away. Then... someone had a brilliant idea- Let's go into that  cafe and order something, and we'd sneakily devour the chicken. We did! 4 girls, 1 bottle of wine, 1 sneaked in roast chicken. #winebffsinaction We tried to be discrete (LOL, which I doubt we were). Thankfully, they didn't chase us out and... mission accomplished! It was epic enough for us to look back and laugh at it even till today, such great memories and experiences to reminisce about :D

*Cheers* to more winebff adventures in the coming years! 

Ps: Attached is a picture of... that very bottle of wine 😂

Craziest travel experience was a trip to South Africa where I stayed in a safari lodge and had a chance to see the big 5 and catch some of the wild and ferocious animals up close. During one of the night game rides, a lion suddenly attacked one of our tour group members while she was taking some photographs and luckily the local tour guide fired a warning shot in the air with his rifle and the animal backed away. Fortunately for the victim, she suffered some scratches and was in a shock but otherwise nothing serious. Philip Tong

message:
"Up till 2 years ago, I was deathly afraid of water. I wouldn’t swim, snorkel, and if I happened to be in water, my feet had to touch the ground. If I couldn’t feel the bottom below my feet, I would freak out and struggle to grab onto something, anything. I had a rocky pool session which to me was insanely horrifying - how do you actually breathe underwater? What if my equipment malfunctioned?? I was so nervous leading up to our first dive in Tioman. And I’ll never forget the fear I had in my heart when I did my first big leap into the ocean. My heart was throbbing with a mix of horror and excitement and adrenaline, and I wasn’t sure what to expect. But the moment we went down under on our first dive, and I opened my eyes to the deep blue, saw my first school of fish, clownfish, octopus… all my fears just went up in a cloud of smoke. What was I so afraid of in the first place? Deep down we’re in a whole new world… and it was amazing. It’s like meditating - all you hear are the bubbles, the sounds of the ocean, and you don’t think about anything else besides enjoying your dive."

Credit: @wandersugar

Kudos for not letting fear get in the way @wandersugar!

You may have heard of longjing tea (dragon well tea), but did you know it's mostly produced in Hangzhou?

There are many tea plantations as well as tea houses within Meijiawu. There, you can fancy a cup of hot longjing tea which is especially good for the chilly weather. 
There are different grades which go for 20, 30 or even 100 yuan a portion. We're not tea connoisseurs and can't really tell the difference but Clara found the tea very bitter while Kenneth had four full cups!

message:
One of the most beautiful parks we've ever come across.

The Bamboo-Lined Path at Yunqi is home to some of the oldest trees in Hangzhou. There's a long stretch of bamboos that line the path from the park's entrance that is very similar to Kyoto's Arashiyama Bamboo Grove. The park is quite vast and one can spend up to three hours walking up to the highest point in the park.

This place is relatively unknown to both foreign and domestic tourists so crowds are absent. It's a good place to catch some fresh air or to stretch your legs.

message:
As we were on #TheMysteryTrip, we weren't able do any research about what to do or eat in Hangzhou.

Luckily for us though, the city is sprawling with good food. Be it restaurants, hole-in-the-wall shops, street stalls, there's definitely something for everyone.

We tried Grandmother's House (外婆家) which is a large restaurant chain in China that typically serves Hangzhou cuisine. The cuisine is characterised by rich yet light variations of Chinese dishes.

The most popular dish here is Dongpo Pork (红烧肉) which literally melts in your mouth! Dishes on average cost 20-40RMB each with is very reasonable for the quality! And yes, this was a meal for two! - Kenneth

message:
West Lake is the epitome of classical Chinese beauty and considered to be one of the most picturesque sights in China.

A must-see when visiting Hangzhou, this man-made 6.5 square km lake provides amazing views from all corners. There are "Ten Scenes" of West Lake which include "Three Pools Mirroring the Moon", "Melting Snow on Broken Bridge" and the featured "Sunset Glow over Leifeng Pagoda".

There's also a famous evening show, "Impression West Lake", that exhibits music and dance against the landscape and waters of West Lake.

message:
Cynthia (@thlovecarousel on Instagram) recounts how she did not have an itinerary during her solo trip yet she thoroughly enjoyed herself. Sounds very similar to The Mystery Trip the Travel Interns will be embarking on.

"My first solo trip to Melbourne was one that was out of my comfort zone. I had never travelled alone, and never travelled out of SEA. Being in a completely new environment didn't overwhelm me, instead, it made me curious. I wanted to explore every single place, learn about their history, see what they had to offer. I didn't plan my itinerary, and that was what made it fun. I had impromptu visits to different places with different friends I made in Melbourne, and it was the most carefree thing to be able to do.

Of course, many travel for different reasons, but I feel that there's so much more than just going to touristy spots and for shopping. There's so much a country has to offer, their culture, the beautiful sceneries, even the interactions with the locals is something we can learn so much from." - Cynthia

We admire your courage to travel solo! Looks like it was definitely worth it! Thanks for sharing!
